2020-07-15 06:47:10-05:00,What Time is the Tax Deadline Today?,"Tax Day 2020 has finally arrived! Thanks to the coronavirus pandemic, the April 15 deadline was pushed back to July 15 this year . So, if you haven't already filed your 2019 federal income tax return (and paid any tax due), today's the day to get moving. But if you're literally waiting until the last minute, you ought to at least know when that last minute arrives. Paper Returns – The Postmark Rules Some people are old fashioned and still like to fill out paper tax forms. If they owe any money with their return, they're likely to write out a paper check to the IRS for the amount due. If that's you, make sure the envelope is postmarked by July 15. But don't expect your post office to stay open until midnight on Tax Day like they used to years ago (sometimes with bands playing and snacks available), so make sure you get there before their regular hours expire if your hand delivering your return at the postal counter. E-filed Returns – The Stroke of Midnight If you're filing an electronic return – like about 90% of taxpayers these days – you must e-file your tax forms by midnight tonight.",IRS,en,Kiplinger Washington Editors
2020-07-15 06:45:50-05:00,Tax Day is Here! File Your Tax Return Today or Face the Consequences,"Happy Tax Day 2020! We normally ""celebrate"" the tax deadline on April 15, but the IRS pushed the due date back to July 15 this year because of the coronavirus pandemic. So, if you haven't already filed your 2019 federal income tax return and paid any tax due, you have until midnight tonight to get it done. (You can request an extension to file your return until October 15 , but you still have to pay what you owe today.) If you don't act in time, here's a glimpse of the IRS interest and penalties you may face: Interest Interest accrues on the unpaid balance and compounds daily from July 15 until you pay the balance in full. The current interest rate for underpayments is 3% (for third quarter of 2020). Late Payment Penalty The late payment penalty is 0.5% of the tax owed after July 15 for each month, or part of a month, the tax remains unpaid. The penalty is capped at 25% of the amount owed. The rate jumps to 1% ten days after the IRS issues a final notice of intent to levy or seize property.",IRS,en,Kiplinger Washington Editors
2020-07-15 06:44:10-05:00,File a Tax Extension Now to Beat Today's Deadline,"Federal income tax returns are due today (July 15)! However, if you can't submit your return before the stroke of midnight, you need to request a filing extension instead . The extension is automatic – you don't even need a reason for putting off your tax return – but you still have to ask for it. Once you do that, you won't have to file your 2019 federal tax return until October 15, 2020. 12 Tax Deadlines for July 15 (It's Not Just the Due Date for Your Tax Return) You still have to pay any taxes due, though. The extension is just for filing your return…not for paying what you owe. So, estimate how much tax you'll owe (if any) when you do file your return and pay that amount now. But make sure you don't estimate too low, because the IRS will charge you interest if you're short. Penalties might be tacked on, too. You can request an extension by filing Form 4868 or by making an electronic tax payment. Either way, you need to act by midnight tonight. For more information, see Tax Extension: How to Get More Time to File Your Tax Return .",IRS,en,Kiplinger Washington Editors
2020-07-15 06:43:10-05:00,Estimated Tax Payments Are Due Today,"Our tax system operates on a ""pay-as-you-go"" basis, which means the IRS wants its cut of your income when you earn it. For employees, the government gets paid through tax withholding each time you get a paycheck. Retirees can have taxes withheld from Social Security payments and retirement plan distributions, too. However, if you're self-employed or don't have taxes withheld from other sources of taxable income (such as interest, dividends or capital gains), it's up to you to periodically pay the IRS by making estimated tax payments. Normally, estimated taxes for income earned from January 1 to March 31 is due on April 15, while estimated taxes for income earned from April 1 to May 31 is typically due on June 15. However, because of the coronavirus pandemic, the April 15 and June 15 deadlines for this year were pushed back until July 15. So, for anyone making 2020 estimated tax payments, your first payment of the year is due today! What Are the Income Tax Brackets for 2020 vs. 2019? Use Form 1040-ES to calculate and pay your estimated taxes.",IRS,en,Kiplinger Washington Editors
